BEGIN_PGML
Write an equation in the form [`y=\ldots`] suggested by the pattern in the table.

>> [@DataTable(
  [
    [[PGML('[`x`]'),
      rowbottom => '2',
      midrule => '1',],
     PGML('[`y`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`[$x[0]]`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[0]]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`[$x[1]]`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[1]]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`[$x[2]]`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[2]]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`[$x[3]]`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[3]]`]'),
    ],
    [PGML('[`[$x[4]]`]'),
     PGML('[`[$y[4]]`]'),
    ],
  ],
      align => 'rl',
      valign => 'middle',);@]* <<

[_]{$eq}{20}

END_PGML

############################################################
# Solution
############################################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION
Each [`y`]-value is [`[$m]`] times what the corresponding [`x`]-value is. So the equation is [`[$eq]\text{.}`]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

